 An exception is an error condition during a program execution. PL/SQL supports programmers to catch such conditions using EXCEPTION block in the program and an 
 appropriate action is taken against the error condition. There are two types of exceptions âˆ’
-System-defined exceptions
-User-defined exceptions

Syntax for exception handling:
ECLARE 
   <declarations section> 
BEGIN 
   <executable command(s)> 
EXCEPTION 
   <exception handling goes here > 
   WHEN exception1 THEN  
      exception1-handling-statements  
   WHEN exception2  THEN  
      exception2-handling-statements  
   WHEN exception3 THEN  
      exception3-handling-statements 
   ........ 
   WHEN others THEN 
      exception3-handling-statements 
END;

Example:
DECLARE 
   c_id customers.id%type := 8; 
   c_name customerS.Name%type; 
   c_addr customers.address%type; 
BEGIN 
   SELECT  name, address INTO  c_name, c_addr 
   FROM customers 
   WHERE id = c_id;  
   DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE ('Name: '||  c_name); 
   DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE ('Address: ' || c_addr); 

EXCEPTION 
   WHEN no_data_found THEN 
      dbms_output.put_line('No such customer!'); 
   WHEN others THEN 
      dbms_output.put_line('Error!'); 
END; 
/

